reviewText: Somewhat enjoyable, but don't expect too much. I bought this set just for "Invisible Invaders".  The price is fair, for what you get.

The package of the 2-CD set was supposed to have 2 movies ('Strange' and 'Invaders') on one CD, and the other two movies on the second. However, both CDs included were idenical: both were of the first CD, with the same movies as the first. Somebody wasn't paying attention when packing these things, I suspect...

My husband suffered a traumatic brain injury and all he thinks about is stuff from the past.  He wanted the movie Journey to the Seventh Planet.  I got him this 4 pack and he loved them.  For todays standards, they are funny to see what the future would be like from the 60's mind frame.  I would recommend these to kill an afternoon with.

I ordered this DVD hoping I would get the "Invaders from Mars 1953 version" but didn't so ordered yet another movie! Now have some Sixty dollars invested. Ordered a VHS movie but the last 20-30 minutes was so scratchy it was a loss of money. I'm sure a lot of movies are not checked before they are sent out. I have 8,yes 8 VHS machines and 5 DVD machines and they can not all be bad. I do know how to clean tape heads. Oh,well that's life.....

they are putting the double features together in one standard size case.its a clearcase so its double sided label too bad it doesn't have the trivia facts still on the case. it about the same price as the double disc so it is a good deal and takes less space than 2 double feature packages. i hope they re release th entire collection as 4 movie sets.

Aliens arrived in 1950s and main characters are having a hard time combating them since the aliens and the government have a joint agreement. I do wish Invaders from Mars was the original, but this 1980s offering is good, too.

Personally I bought this for one film and that was Invisible Invaders. It was a B film that fought hard to get the B, but because I was about 8 years old when I saw it and it was in the mid 60's, films were hardly as gory as they are now. This one scared snot out of me for that time and even today with the recollection of those days it is still unsettling.

This collection gets five stars for Strange Invaders alone. This was a staple on Cinemax back in the 1980s. Seems like every time I played hooky from school, this movie was on. Yes, it's cheesy, b-grade science fiction. In my world, that's a five-star description. The Tobe Hooper remake of Invaders from Mars is fun. The other two flicks are older, but just as much fun. The price is right, if you're not addicted to the polished turds hollywood's producing these days, you'll dig it. If you remember seeing these on cable tv back in the day, you'll love it.

I bought this set mainly for Tobe Hooper's version of 'Invaders From Mars'. Liked the original too, but this highly campy version is very good. All movies had good picture quality. Had never seen 'Invisible Invaders'. Must have missed that one growing up. The best part of 'Strange Invaders' is the beautiful Nancy Allen.

These movies aren't bad, but they aren't the best of the classic scifi bunch.

The big surprise for me was Strange Invaders from the 1980s. It's a slow starter, but a very good plot.

The rest are OK. Be warned that the Journey to the Seventh Planet's audio does not sync with the picture. It's storyline as been done on so many other scifi shows - including Star Trek. I'm just not sure if this was one of the first or not.

Overall, it's not a bad buy for $5, but if you want scifi you can't stop watching, Grab Destination Moon, Quatermass, Colossus - The Forbin Project, or Demon Seed (with Julie Christie).

I bought this set out of curiosity and for the remake of 'Invaders From Mars', but the '80s remake left me wanting to watch the original '50s version again. As for 'Strange Invaders' and 'Invisible Invaders', well, they're both entertainingly funny in a bad way.
